Path: godot/tutorials/navigation/navigation_optimizing_performance.rst
Summary: This section discusses common performance issues related to NavigationAgent path queries and provides strategies for optimization.
Tip: Avoid unnecessary path resets and queries every frame in NavigationAgent scripts. Avoid updating all NavigationAgent paths in the same frame.

Logical errors and wasteful operations in custom NavigationAgent scripts are common causes of performance issues, such as resetting the path every single frame. By default, NavigationAgents are optimized to query new paths only when the target position changes, the navigation map changes, or they are forced too far from the desired path distance.

For example, when an AI should move to the player, the target position should not be set to the player's position every frame, as this queries a new path each time. Instead, compare the distance from the current target position to the player's position and only set a new target position when the player has moved too far away.

Do not check beforehand if a target position is reachable every frame. This check is equivalent to an expensive path query. If a new path will be requested anyway should the position be reachable, query a path directly. By examining the last position of the returned path, if that position is within a "reachable" distance to the checked position, it answers the "is this position reachable?" question. This avoids performing two full path queries every frame for the same NavigationAgent.

Divide the total number of NavigationAgents into update groups or use random timers so that they do not all request new paths in the same frame.
---CHUNK---
